Part Three - Observations and answers to questions

Based on [visually inspecting] the scatterplot of depth vs price, most diamonds are between what values of depth? 60 & 64
Whats the correlation of depth vs.price? `r cor(diamonds\(price,diamonds\)depth)
This correlation is too low to suggest a strong relationship between depth and price.

Section Three - Create a scatterplot of price vs carat and omit the top 1% of price and carat values.

Part Two - Create a scatterplot of price vs.volume (x * y * z). Create a new variable for volume in the diamonds data frame. This will be useful in a later exercise. Dont make any adjustments to the plot just yet.

Part Three - Create data frame with volume > 0 & < 800 then provide observations on the above graph and answers to questions:

It is a very steep, increasing curve that is over-plotted. There also seem to be some erroneous outliers, that should likely be ignored. There are also 20 diamonds with 0 volume! Also, including only diamonds with volume >0 and <800, the correlation of price to volume is equal to 0.9235455

Section Four - Adjust the transparency of the points and add a linear model to the plot.

####Answers to questions I believe their are better models than the linear one presented above to predict price based on volume. For instance, a quadratic model like y= x + I(x^2) would likely be a closer fit. That said, both lose effectiveness above the 150 mark for volume.
